The code statements that lead to the bug are:
```java
publishContentHeader(new ContentHeaderBody(properties, bodySize));
```
```java
if(bodySize > _connection.getMaxMessageSize())
```
Reason:
The `publishContentHeader` method is called without a conditional check to ensure that the `bodySize` does not exceed the maximum allowed limit. This oversight allows messages larger than the permitted size to be published, leading to errors or unexpected behavior.

The code statements that fix the bug are:
```java
if(bodySize > _connection.getMaxMessageSize())
{
    properties.dispose();
    closeChannel(ErrorCodes.MESSAGE_TOO_LARGE,
                 "Message size of " + bodySize + " greater than allowed maximum of " + _connection.getMaxMessageSize());
}
else
{
    publishContentHeader(new ContentHeaderBody(properties, bodySize));
}
```
Reason:
The added conditional check ensures that `publishContentHeader` is only called if the `bodySize` is within the allowed limit. If the size exceeds the maximum, the method disposes of the properties and closes the channel with an appropriate error message, thus preventing the publication of oversized messages.

